The article is a statement by the President on World Day Against Child Labor. The President expresses concern about the 215 million children worldwide who are forced to work in dangerous conditions instead of enjoying their childhood. He praises his Secretary of Labor for efforts to address child labor both domestically and abroad and announces a commitment of $60 million to support global initiatives to reduce child labor. The Department of Labor has also taken steps to improve protections for child workers in the United States and has increased law enforcement efforts. A conference on child labor was hosted jointly by the Department of State and the Department of Labor, demonstrating a commitment to a comprehensive approach to the issue. The President emphasizes the importance of addressing the root causes of child labor, such as lack of access to education and poverty, and calls for a collective effort to create a world where children are free from exploitative labor.